1. **DynamicProxyConverter RCE** (most critical) - XML-controlled InvocationHandler (e.g., EventHandler) passed to Proxy.newProxyInstance() enables direct OS command execution - CVE-2021-21344/CVE-2013-7285
2. **DefaultMapper.realClass() arbitrary class loading** - Class.forName() with XML-supplied class names is the central class-loading sink for all gadget chains
3. **SerializationMembers.callWriteReplace/callWriteObject** - Method.invoke() on deserialized objects enables writeReplace/writeObject gadget chains
4. **BeanProvider getter/setter injection** - Method.invoke() on deserialized bean objects enables getter/setter gadget chains
5. **CGLIBEnhancedConverter** - CGLIB proxy deserialization with attacker-controlled callbacks
6. **AbstractAttributedCharacterIteratorAttributeConverter** - Static method invocation on attacker-controlled classes
7. **AnyTypePermission bypass** - Always-true permission unconditionally bypasses SecurityMapper type restrictions
8. **SecurityMapper design flaw** - Class.forName() called before permission check, enabling static initializer execution even for "forbidden" classes
9. **CustomObjectInputStream.resolveClass** - Class.forName() in Java serialization bridge enables nested gadget chains
10. **PureJavaReflectionProvider.resolveClass** - Class.forName() in reflection provider deserialization path

All vulnerabilities stem from XStream's fundamental design of using class names from untrusted XML to load and instantiate classes without adequate default restrictions.
